{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fca6455-81c7-4fc5-963a-90e624f111ea","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** an existing `.dmp` file, here are your best options:\n\n**`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <path-to-dump.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n**Visual Studio** (Windows):\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich UI for inspecting threads, exceptions, and memory.\n\n**lldb + SOS** (Linux/macOS):\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core <dump.dmp>\n```\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fdb64f77-c5e2-4354-8527-7f2752e670b0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze an existing dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing the dump file directly.","outputTokens":360},"id":"c1471489-ec1a-4cf1-b98f-6e654f161862","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:05:46.980Z","parentId":"cb82a144-a7c3-4b82-81c5-a751e2ad65a7"}
